Goal: Learn how to access and modify raster and vector data

R Packages Needed

library(sp)
library(rgdal)
library(raster)
library(latticeExtra)

Set Your Working Directory

Change this to the correct path name on your machine

setwd("~/Documents/Intro-Spatial-R/module3")

This is the syntax for the path on an Apple/Mac for a subfolder in the Documents directory. To find out your current working directory in `R` run the command getwd() and use setwd() to set you working directory. Help for loaded R functions can be accessed by running ?function_name on the command line, e.g. ?setwd

Read in Shapefiles

Here we import a polygon boundary of the state of Utah and a set of polygons representing game management units within the state.

utah.wgs84 <- readOGR(dsn = "data", layer = "utah_wgs84") # Utah border, for "pretty" plotting
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "data", layer: "utah_wgs84"
## with 1 features
## It has 59 fields
deer_units <- readOGR(dsn = "data", layer = "deerrange_UT") # Data on deer/elk management units
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "data", layer: "deerrange_UT"
## with 29 features
## It has 16 fields

Make a basic plot with coloring based on UName

plot(deer_units, 
     axes = TRUE, # adds the coordinate ranges to the axes
     col = deer_units$UName, # colors the polygons based on UName
     main = "Utah Game Management Units" # adds main title to plot
     )
plot(utah.wgs84, add = TRUE) # Add the Utah border for reference

Use the spplot function from sp package to provide coloring and a legend based on the UName (unit name) attribute of the management units. So, essentially the same plot as above, just a different method.

spplot(deer_units, # spatial object (data set) to plot
       c("UName"), # names of columns to plot
       scales = list(draw = TRUE), # this adds the coordinate values to the plot
       main = "Utah Game Management Units" # adds title to map
       # ,sp.layout = list("sp.polygons", utah.wgs84) # adds Utah border to map within call to `spplot` function
       ) +
      layer(sp.polygons(utah.wgs84)) # alternative way to add layers to map; requires `latticeExtra` package, but can be easier to read and follow

Querying data of a vector (shapefile)

Querying the data in a shapefile is much the same as querying any other data frame in R. For example, if you want to look at the data only for the West Desert unit:

Or perhaps you just want to have a quick look at how many deer are in the Box Elder unit:

deer_units@data$DEER[deer_units@data$UName == "Box Elder"]
## [1] 15180

Note that these are base R methods for indexing. There are also several frequently used packages that have been built to help with manipulation of data as needs become more complex, e.g. plyr, dplyr, data.table are three well known packages.

Calculate a new field for vector data

Calculating a new field is as easy as adding a new column to any other data frame in R. Say we want to calcualte a new field from the existing data, such as the total number of adult deer and elk in each management unit:

# tot_deer_elk is the field we want to add to the deer_units data frame
deer_units$tot_deer_elk <- deer_units$DEER + deer_units$ELK

Convert vector to raster

Perhaps we want to add some data from a raster, such as a gridded surface of NDVI. NDVI may be indicative of deer and elk population abundance and/or reproductive success. Calculations of NDVI for a given pixel always result in a number that ranges from minus one (-1) to plus one (+1); however, no green leaves gives a value close to zero. A zero means no vegetation and close to +1 (0.8 - 0.9) indicates the highest possible density of green leaves. More info on NDVI

First, let’s read in the NDVI raster surface

ndvi500m <- raster("data/N200530602133CBR_v1.1.dat", format = "ENVI")
ndvi500m
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 4288, 4171, 17885248  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -121.612, -104.2328, 27.83958, 45.70625  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : /Users/wwdillon/Documents/IALE2015_StudentWorkshop/IALE2015_gisRcourse/data/N200530602133CBR_v1.1.dat 
## names       : N200530602133CBR_v1.1 
## values      : -32768, 32767  (min, max)
names(ndvi500m) <- "ndvi" # Change raster attribute name to something meaningful
ndvi500m <- ndvi500m/(ndvi500m@data@max+1)
ndvi500m
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 4288, 4171, 17885248  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -121.612, -104.2328, 27.83958, 45.70625  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : in memory
## names       : ndvi 
## values      : -0.3738403, 0.4416504  (min, max)

Note that the projection is in decimal degrees and thus the grain and extent are also given in decimal degrees. Next, check that the projections of our layers are all the same:

all.equal(proj4string(deer_units), proj4string(utah.wgs84), proj4string(ndvi500m))
## [1] TRUE

The all.equal function returns TRUE if the objects are all the same, and FALSE otherwise. So, all of these layers have exactly the same proj4 string. This is important if we want to draw a map with these surfaces overlain correctly.

Plotting the layers we see that the NDVI surface is much larger than our area of interest, in fact covering much of the southwestern United States.

plot(ndvi500m, main = "NDVI")
plot(utah.wgs84, add = TRUE)
plot(deer_units, add = TRUE)

So, we can crop the raster to an area that’s a little smaller to make a map of NDVI across the deer ranges in Utah.

ndvi_utah <- crop(ndvi500m, extent(utah.wgs84))
ndvi_utah
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 1202, 1200, 1442400  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -114.0453, -109.0453, 36.99375, 42.00208  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : in memory
## names       : ndvi 
## values      : -0.01159668, 0.239624  (min, max)
plot(ndvi_utah, main = "NDVI - Utah")
plot(utah.wgs84, add = TRUE)
plot(deer_units, add = TRUE)

Now we can create a new raster of using the management units based on the NDVI raster’s grain and extent that was cropped for Utah. This is used to demonstrate masking the data from a raster with a larger extent.

system.time(deer_units.rast <- rasterize(deer_units, ndvi_utah, deer_units$UNum)) # note this took about 5 seconds on my 16 GB RAM laptop
##    user  system elapsed 
##   5.580   0.033   5.651
deer_units.rast
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 1202, 1200, 1442400  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -114.0453, -109.0453, 36.99375, 42.00208  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : in memory
## names       : layer 
## values      : 1, 30  (min, max)
names(deer_units.rast) <- "UNum" # Rename this to the correct value

## Examine plots; colors correspond to the value of UNum
plot(deer_units.rast, main = "Utah Deer/Elk Management Units (raster)") # note that this retains the extent of the input raster
plot(deer_units, add = TRUE)
plot(utah.wgs84 , add = TRUE)

Not demonstrated here is the method to convert rasters to polygons. This can be accomplished using the rasterToPolygons function from the raster package.

Subsetting/masking data

We can use the deer range raster, which matches (and must match) the extent, grain, and projection of the cropped NDVI data, to mask NDVI raster based on the management units. Masking can be done using either another raster or spatial object (e.g. polygons)

# First using the raster we created
ndvi_deer.mask1 <- mask(ndvi_utah, deer_units.rast)
# Second using the original spatial polygons
ndvi_deer.mask2 <- mask(ndvi_utah, deer_units)
# Compare the results of the two masking methods
ndvi_deer.mask1
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 1202, 1200, 1442400  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -114.0453, -109.0453, 36.99375, 42.00208  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : in memory
## names       : ndvi 
## values      : 0, 0.239624  (min, max)
ndvi_deer.mask2
## class       : RasterLayer 
## dimensions  : 1202, 1200, 1442400  (nrow, ncol, ncell)
## resolution  : 0.004166667, 0.004166667  (x, y)
## extent      : -114.0453, -109.0453, 36.99375, 42.00208  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : +proj=longlat +datum=WGS84 +no_defs +ellps=WGS84 +towgs84=0,0,0 
## data source : in memory
## names       : ndvi 
## values      : 0, 0.239624  (min, max)
all.equal(ndvi_deer.mask1, ndvi_deer.mask2)
## [1] TRUE
plot(ndvi_deer.mask1, main = "NDVI Utah Deer/Elk Management Units")
plot(ndvi_deer.mask2, add = TRUE) # note nothing changes, exactly the same plot
plot(utah.wgs84, add = TRUE)
plot(deer_units, add = TRUE)

To generate this masked raster we didn’t need to convert the polygons to a raster, but this demonstrates the capabilities of processing from whichever data type you begin with.

Now we’ll calculate the mean NDVI for each deer/elk management unit and add it to the data frame - a hint of whats to come in the next module. Here we add the column avg.ndvi1 to the deer_units data frame by extracting it from the ndvi_utah.

deer_units$avg.ndvi <- extract(
      ndvi_utah, # the raster to extract values frome
      deer_units, # the point/line/polygon defining the locations to extract/summarise values for
      fun = mean, na.rm=T # the function to apply to the cells in those zones
      )
summary(deer_units)

Notice in the summary that we get a bit of a funny looking result from the extract function. An investigation of the class of that variable reveals that the result is a matrix, even though it is only a single column. This normal behavior for SpatialPolygons* or SpatialLines* objects. We just want a numeric vector in our data frame, which is accomplished with a call to as.vector. If this was not changed to a vector then it would cause errors when trying to export the object as a new shapefile (learned from this experience).

class(deer_units$avg.ndvi)
## [1] "matrix"
deer_units$avg.ndvi <- as.vector(deer_units$avg.ndvi)

Now let’s make a map of the averaged NDVI for each of the deer and elk management units across Utah

spplot(deer_units, c("avg.ndvi"), scales = list(draw = TRUE), main = "NDVI Utah Deer/Elk Management Units") +
      layer(sp.polygons(utah.wgs84))

Adding attributes by joining data

The deer/elk management units are smaller areas within larger game management units in Utah.

mgt_units <- readOGR(dsn = "data", layer = "deerunits_UT")
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "data", layer: "deerunits_UT"
## with 30 features
## It has 10 fields
plot(mgt_units, main = "Utah Game Management Units - Deer/Elk Subset")
plot(utah.wgs84, add = TRUE)
plot(deer_units, add = TRUE, col = deer_units$UName)

Notice that the colun names don’t match up precisely, so we will rename the column that we wan’t to base the join on in one of the data frames to match the other. This can also be done by column number index, but a common column name makes things much clearer.

names(mgt_units@data)[names(mgt_units@data) == "UNIT_NUM"] <- "UNum"
deer_units@data <- merge(deer_units@data, # data frame to join more data to
                         mgt_units@data, # data frame to join data from
                         by = "UNum", # the column name to base the merge on; this can also be the column name if it is the same for both data frames 
                         all.x = TRUE # adds extra rows with NAs when there are no matches in second object; in other words, retains all of deer_units data
                         )

Write out spatial polygons shapefiles

We will export the deer_units object as a new shapefile to the outdata subfolder.

writeOGR(deer_units, # the object we want to save
         dsn = "data/outdata", # the path to the folder we want to save it in
         layer = "deerrange_UT2", # the name we want to give the layer
         driver = "ESRI Shapefile", # the drive provides the proper extension
         overwrite_layer = TRUE # this enables overwriting an existing file with the same name
         )
